                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d459">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">881.113/34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Diplomatic Agent and Consul General at Tangier</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Blake</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-02T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 2, 1936—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>12. Your 20, August 20, 5 p.m. In view of the facts and opinions reported in your
                    recent telegrams, especially your 23 August 28 6 p.m., the Department considers
                    it unwise to acquiesce in any way in the application of the Dahir of August 17,
                    1936, at the present time. You should therefore limit your reply to Resident
                    General to an acknowledgment of the receipt of his communication, adding that
                    the matter has been referred to the Department for its consideration.</p>
                <p>If and when further events in Spain and North Africa make a revision of the
                    Department’s position advisable, you will be instructed accordingly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
